Antwarp 4 march 1681
ch
S. my last to you was on the 18: past, sence recd. yd of 7 & 15 ditto
I amsorrj for yd indisposition yett I hope with the approaching sent
that you will be quite rides of yd trouble some compaynion & in a
condition to menage yd concernes to yd content: what you shalldo
about the desired redds will be to content, what you shall doubout
I take not ice that gjles nash hath made no silver marck for
some time & demands £13:10 p. cloths, for them because thay
use oneles they use be silver marck our Jesuits will not buy them
because they use to have them from vermeulen & now they
would faine have them from mee as I sell yd perped & others
goods:, so shall easely make more then £27: for them & if not
they may lett f. lye by I have had of late some curiousgloche
whites of £1310: which I sold for £30 & £31, which I rekon
would to so if you finde the bw. silver marck good with 5 p
shall make atryall, butt to have refus all, can not incline to where
fore leave the case to yd advise, because itt must not be onely to
beassorted, & in hopes to advance a penny for ones paines my to
thanckes for yd advise of the concernes of RM flnerrcome
sence the least comission wee heardno more about itt tis fure
RM„ will nevercome to England for as longeither of the parties
lives, I doubt they will hardely be separated, so shall keep itt onely
for my governo & nott more any thing of the matter except I should
be there unto desired & so with kindt saluts remaine

S my last to you was on the 22: past. sence recd yd. 10 & 14 ditto asto
the cloth N.168„ is you meane 156 sald att ƒ3:18: because N. 150 is brouy
in the resting goods & sold this day att ƒ6:6 N 156 sold to I idocus desadelaer
att ƒ3„18 which if did cost 1of is yd faulte, because you have noted
itt 7:6 in a note of the prijses, & I sold itt up on the pattarne att
Brussell & by yd note, without takeing notice of the cloth when
I sent ist away & to yd satisfaction in close you please tohime yd
note returned, shall do itt in answer to you as to N. 153„ & 155 in ½when
the rest is sold & noted nneder N.153 as to the bay for yd acctt. mee thinckis
you are in the right, for I formd him out concerning our acctt. cut
where by you supose I over charge you £360:-:- hereyon have
the dates of all yd bills on mee for yd acctt. last yeare each noted
consecutinely as they are on the acctt. curitt sece besides them
you will finde you self s harged with £150:- remitted in my
owne bill on yd of John derichebourght, butt that is trwice brought
in creditt, so I supose the mustake lijes not there & the 2 firsts
bills of the acctt. 1680„ ballanced oft: june are which I have p
for yd honour of T.H. which are now in lace & m. Herreyns
loose no time to procure sentence against him, when either
he must pay rumaway breake, or brought in prison of what passes
you will have advise the £47:13„6 shall accept & exspect patt
& in voyce of the assortement of desired spanish cloathes & whilst
I remaine with kins saluts

In Antwarp 4 march
London Abrams vivians
th
S. my last to you was on the 26: patt. with a bill for £90 in vanden
broeck for my acctt. which I hope you shall have duely recd. as also the
valew, sence is come to handes yd of 14 & 18 pass. I observe the packes
N. 24 „ 2„ 28 are now also aboard nelson, god in heaven send him
speedly & well over, for wee want the goods att markett I am sorry
poore nathan toldroid should leave his wife & child remnso a
conditions I observe you recd. N. 8 & fomd them better & then formar
truely that I did not exspect I have assorted all the packetts as yd
first order was butt now all is gou, accept what is yett all worch
& will be about 10 dayes before ready where fore dispatch such
orders for what you might want most, to assort & sett off the rest
the better N.12 will come by longesea with the linmen & supose
with you before this & then you see all, I could advise you to send
pattarnes of laces you would have & senditt in yd letters, for itt will
pay no postidgehere, & I tought itt should be I in cane each patt. should
of ayd long I can al wayes make itt as long you will here
then returned in packts itt should be the better to understand theright
meaning & instruction for proceeding: if you inntye or impime the goods
& show them loose itt will make a better shew in selling, & lay them
up on ablack cloth, which setts them off mightley & makes a fine shew
as for the bale N.31 leave itt as itt is & lett itt be send forward & contramas
buying for I would faine see the sundry goods now underway before
wee proceed any firther for I doubt wee mett noth with chipping though
I hope the goods will prove well, which by the patt. N. 24 onely doth
promise, so exspect so see the goods first before race proceed buying att
present have butt very little by mee - you draw £100: att 36:1 for
my acctt. that I shall accept butt pass itt to yd acctt because I havee
payd, or remitted you more then £100 st more then what is dueon
my acctt. s inclused the bale N.35„ besides you are not less advanced
in ijd acctt flemish, where fore lett mee intreat you not tobe
